The notebook: The notebook should be created using rmarkdown or Quarto (like other assignments). The notebook should have a title.

The Presentation: Present your results in 5-10 minutes. To make the presentation using Rmarkdown, do the follows:

- In Rstudio -> File -> New File -> R markdown

- In the left panel, click to Presentation -> Click OK

- Now you have an Rmarkdown that can be knitted to be a html presentation

  • You can also use the Rmd templates of the class slides.

  • You can also use Quarto to create the presentation: In Rstudio -> File -> New File -> Quarto Presentation…

  • You do not need to rerun all the codes for the presentation. For example, to show the model comparison, you just need to show the image of the model comparison instead of running all the models again.

    • http://zevross.com/blog/2017/06/19/tips-and-tricks-for-working-with-images-and-figures-in-r-markdown-documents/

library(ggplot2)
library(gganimate)
library(dplyr)
## 1. Distribution of Patient Ages
ggplot(df, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, fill = "steelblue", color = "white") +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Patient Ages",
    x = "Age",
    y = "Frequency",
    caption = "Histogram showing the distribution of patient ages."
  )

## 2. Average Length of Stay by Season
df %>%
  group_by(season) %>%
  summarise(avg_los = mean(los, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = season, y = avg_los, fill = season)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Average Length of Stay by Season",
    x = "Season",
    y = "Average Length of Stay",
    caption = "Bar plot comparing the average length of stay across seasons."
  )

## 3. Total Charges by Month
df %>%
  group_by(moa) %>%

    caption = "Bar plot showing total charges incurred each month."
  )

## 4. Gender Proportion
df %>%
  count(sex) %>%

## The visualizations reveal several patterns in the hospital discharge data. The distribution of patient ages shows that the majority are concentrated within certain age groups, while the average length of stay varies significantly by season, with Winter showing the longest stays. Total charges peak in certain months, suggesting seasonal factors influencing hospital utilization. The proportion of male and female patients is relatively balanced, but teenage female patients are admitted more in specific months. ICU admissions are clustered in high-demand months. Finally, charges vary across providers, age groups, and patient conditions, highlighting operational differences. These insights can help optimize resource allocation and patient care.

III. Predictive Models

Continue with the data from part I. Make sure you do not have any missing values in the data. Use the follows as the target and input variables:

Target Variable: Create the target variable taking value of

  • low if the total charge of a patient (tot) is smaller than the median of the total charge, and

  • high otherwise.

Input Variables:

  • “age”,“sex”,“raceethn”,“provider”,“moa”,“mod”,“admtype”,“campus”, ‘los’
  1. Use filter function to filter out rows where raceethn=='' or admtype==''. Make sure all the categorical variables are factor, numeric variables are numeric. Set Training : Testing Split = 10 : 90
library(dplyr)
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
library(caret)
df <- df %>%
  filter(raceethn != '', admtype != '') %>%
  mutate(
    raceethn = as.factor(raceethn),
    admtype = as.factor(admtype),
    sex = as.factor(sex),
    provider = as.factor(provider),
    moa = as.factor(moa),
    mod = as.factor(mod),
    campus = as.factor(campus),
    age = as.numeric(age),
    los = as.numeric(los),
    tot = as.numeric(tot)
  )
median_tot <- median(df$tot, na.rm = TRUE)
df <- df %>%
  mutate(target = ifelse(tot < median_tot, "low", "high")) %>%
  mutate(target = as.factor(target))
set.seed(42)
train_index <- createDataPartition(df$target, p = 0.1, list = FALSE)
train_data <- df[train_index, ]
test_data <- df[-train_index, ]
  1. Train a decision tree using rpart. Plot the decision tree. Plot the variable importance ranked by the tree.
tree_model <- rpart(target ~ age + sex + raceethn + provider + moa + mod + admtype + campus + los, 
                    data = train_data, method = "class")
rpart.plot(tree_model, main = "Decision Tree for Predicting Total Charges")

importance <- as.data.frame(varImp(tree_model, scale = FALSE))
barplot(importance$Overall, names.arg = rownames(importance), main = "Variable Importance", las = 2, col = "steelblue")

  1. Using caret for this question. Set Training Control to be: Use Cross-Validation of 5 folds across all models. Train & tune at least 2 different models (i.e. two different values for method= in the train function of caret). Plot the hyper-parameter tuning plots for each model.
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)
set.seed(42)
model_tree <- train(target ~ age + sex + raceethn + provider + moa + mod + admtype + campus + los, 
                    data = train_data, 
                    method = "rpart", 
                    trControl = train_control)
library(randomForest)
set.seed(42)
model_rf <- train(target ~ age + sex + raceethn + provider + moa + mod + admtype + campus + los, 
                  data = train_data, 
                  method = "rf", 
                  trControl = train_control)
plot(model_tree, main = "Decision Tree Hyper-Parameter Tuning")

plot(model_rf, main = "Random Forest Hyper-Parameter Tuning")

  1. Plot the comparison of the models in 3.
results <- resamples(list(DecisionTree = model_tree, RandomForest = model_rf))
summary(results)

## The predictive modeling process provided valuable insights into patient charges and their influencing factors. Using a decision tree and random forest, we analyzed how variables like age, gender, provider, and length of stay affect total charges. The random forest model performed better in terms of accuracy and robustness, as shown by cross-validation results. Testing on unseen data confirmed its reliability. When we switched to predicting the length of stay, similar variables showed importance, indicating consistent patterns in patient data. Overall, these models can assist hospitals in predicting patient needs and optimizing operational strategies.
